    </div>

    <!-- CLINICAL EVIDENCE -->
    <h2>Clinical Evidence: What Do Ashwagandha Gummies Actually Do?</h2>

    <p>The clinical evidence for ashwagandha is among the strongest in the entire herbal supplement category. Unlike many adaptogens that rely primarily on traditional use claims, ashwagandha has been evaluated in dozens of randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled trials — the gold standard of clinical evidence.</p>

    <h3>Stress and Cortisol Reduction</h3>

    <p>This is ashwagandha's strongest evidence base. A landmark 2012 study published in the <em>Indian Journal of Psychological Medicine</em> gave 64 adults with chronic stress either 300mg of KSM-66 twice daily or placebo for 60 days. The ashwagandha group showed a <strong>27.9% reduction in serum cortisol</strong> levels and a <strong>69.7% reduction in perceived stress scores</strong> (PSS-10) compared to placebo. These are clinically significant effect sizes that rival some pharmaceutical interventions.</p>

    <p>A follow-up meta-analysis published in the <em>Journal of Alternative and Complementary Medicine</em> (2019) pooled data from 12 RCTs and confirmed: ashwagandha significantly reduces cortisol and stress across multiple study populations, doses, and extract types. The consistency of results across different research groups strengthens the evidence — this is not a single-study finding from a single laboratory.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">69.7%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">reduction in perceived stress scores was measured in the landmark KSM-66 clinical trial — a 60-day RCT of 64 adults with chronic stress. <strong>Cortisol dropped by 27.9% in the ashwagandha group</strong> versus 7.9% in placebo. These effect sizes are exceptional for a non-pharmaceutical intervention and have been replicated across multiple independent studies.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>Sleep Quality</h3>

    <p>Ashwagandha demonstrates meaningful sleep improvement, particularly in people whose poor sleep is driven by stress and anxiety. A 2019 study in <em>Cureus</em> found that 300mg of KSM-66 twice daily for 10 weeks improved sleep quality scores by <strong>72%</strong> on the Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI) in adults with insomnia. Sleep onset latency decreased, total sleep time increased, and sleep efficiency improved.</p>

    <p>The mechanism is indirect — ashwagandha improves sleep primarily by reducing cortisol and anxiety, which are among the most common drivers of insomnia. It does not act as a direct sedative like melatonin or GABA. This means ashwagandha is best suited for stress-related sleep problems rather than circadian rhythm disorders. For more on sleep-specific supplementation, see our guide to the <a href="/best-sleep-gummies/">best sleep gummies</a>.</p>

    <h3>Anxiety Reduction</h3>

    <p>Multiple trials have demonstrated anxiolytic effects. A 2009 study in <em>PLoS ONE</em> compared ashwagandha to psychotherapy and found that 300mg of extract twice daily produced <strong>a 56.5% reduction in Hamilton Anxiety Scale (HAM-A) scores</strong> — comparable to the improvement seen with cognitive behavioral therapy. A separate 2000 study compared ashwagandha to lorazepam (Ativan) and found equivalent anxiolytic effects without the sedation, cognitive impairment, or dependence risk associated with benzodiazepines.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="trending" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Testosterone & Male Health</h4>
        <p>A 2019 <em>American Journal of Men's Health</em> study found 600mg/day of KSM-66 increased testosterone by ~15% and DHEA-S by ~18% in overweight men aged 40-70 after 8 weeks. A separate study in infertile men showed improved sperm count, motility, and testosterone. The effect is likely mediated through cortisol reduction — chronic stress suppresses testosterone, and normalizing cortisol allows testosterone to recover.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="brain" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Cognitive Function</h4>
        <p>A 2017 study in the <em>Journal of Dietary Supplements</em> found 300mg of KSM-66 twice daily significantly improved reaction time, task performance, and attention in healthy adults over 8 weeks. A 2014 study found improvements in both immediate and general memory. These cognitive effects may be secondary to stress and sleep improvement rather than a direct nootropic mechanism.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="fitness" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Exercise Performance</h4>
        <p>A 2015 study in the <em>Journal of the International Society of Sports Nutrition</em> found 300mg of KSM-66 twice daily significantly increased muscle strength (bench press and leg extension), muscle size (arm and chest circumference), and reduced exercise-induced muscle damage versus placebo in resistance-trained men over 8 weeks. Recovery between training sessions also improved.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="heart" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Inflammation & Immunity</h4>
        <p>Ashwagandha demonstrates immunomodulatory and anti-inflammatory properties in clinical studies. A 2021 study found it increased natural killer cell activity and reduced C-reactive protein (CRP), a marker of systemic inflammation. These effects may contribute to the overall "well-being" improvement reported by study participants beyond specific symptom categories.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- THE DOSE PROBLEM -->
    <h2>The Ashwagandha Gummy Dose Problem</h2>

    <p>Here is where many ashwagandha gummies fail. The clinical evidence is clear about effective doses: <strong>300-600mg of standardized extract per day</strong>. But the physical constraints of the gummy format — each gummy weighs 3-5 grams and must contain sugar/sweetener, pectin/gelatin, flavoring, and coloring in addition to the active ingredient — make it difficult to pack 300-600mg of ashwagandha extract into a reasonable serving size.</p>

    <p>The result: many ashwagandha gummies on the market contain only 100-200mg of actual ashwagandha extract per serving — well below the clinical threshold. Some products disguise this by listing a large amount of "ashwagandha root powder" (which contains a much lower concentration of withanolides) rather than standardized extract.</p>

