    <!-- WHO SHOULD NOT TAKE -->
    <h2>Who Should NOT Take Ashwagandha Gummies</h2>

    <p>Ashwagandha is safe for most healthy adults at recommended doses, but it has important contraindications related to its hormonal and immunological effects. These are not theoretical concerns — they are based on ashwagandha's documented pharmacological activity.</p>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
      <p><strong>Thyroid conditions:</strong> Ashwagandha stimulates thyroid hormone production (T3 and T4). A 2018 study in the <em>Journal of Alternative and Complementary Medicine</em> found that 600mg/day of KSM-66 significantly increased both TSH and T4 levels. For people with hypothyroidism on thyroid medication, this effect may require dose adjustment. For people with hyperthyroidism or Graves' disease, ashwagandha could dangerously exacerbate overactive thyroid function. <strong>Do not take ashwagandha if you have any thyroid condition without endocrinologist approval.</strong></p>
    </div>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
      <p><strong>Autoimmune diseases:</strong> Ashwagandha is immunomodulatory — it can both stimulate and regulate immune function. For people with autoimmune conditions (lupus, rheumatoid arthritis, Hashimoto's thyroiditis, multiple sclerosis, type 1 diabetes), this immune modulation may trigger flares or interfere with immunosuppressive medications. While some preliminary research suggests ashwagandha may actually help regulate aberrant immune responses, the evidence is insufficient to recommend it for autoimmune patients without physician supervision.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
      <p><strong>Pregnant or breastfeeding women:</strong> Animal studies suggest ashwagandha may have abortifacient (uterine stimulant) properties at high doses. While no human studies have confirmed this risk, there is insufficient safety data in pregnant or breastfeeding women. The traditional Ayurvedic contraindication against ashwagandha in pregnancy aligns with the precautionary principle. Avoid entirely during pregnancy and lactation.</p>
    </div>

