    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section class="faq-sec">
      <h2>Do Ashwagandha Gummies Work? — Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Do ashwagandha gummies actually work?</summary><p>Yes, when they contain clinically studied extracts (KSM-66 or Sensoril) at adequate doses (300-600mg standardized extract per serving). A 2019 meta-analysis of 12 RCTs found ashwagandha reduced cortisol by 11-32% and anxiety scores by 44-69%. The gummy format does not impair absorption — the critical variable is dose, not delivery format.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>How long does it take for ashwagandha gummies to work?</summary><p>Stress and cortisol reduction become measurable within 2-4 weeks. Full benefits including anxiety relief, sleep improvement, and cognitive enhancement typically manifest at 8-12 weeks. Testosterone and exercise performance benefits require 8-12 weeks. Ashwagandha works by gradually rebalancing the HPA axis, not by acutely sedating the nervous system. See our detailed timeline in <a href="/blog/how-long-does-ashwagandha-take-to-work/">how long does ashwagandha take to work</a>.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What is the best ashwagandha extract for gummies?</summary><p>KSM-66 is the gold standard with 24+ clinical trials. It is a full-spectrum root extract standardized to 5% withanolides. Sensoril is the second-best option, standardized to 10% withanolides with strong evidence for cortisol reduction. Avoid generic, unstandardized extracts — they have inconsistent withanolide levels and limited clinical data.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>How much ashwagandha should be in a gummy?</summary><p>Look for 300-600mg of standardized KSM-66 or 125-250mg of Sensoril per daily serving. Many gummies contain only 100-200mg of generic extract — below the clinical threshold. Always check the Supplement Facts panel for the specific extract name and milligram amount, not just marketing claims on the front of the bottle.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Can you take ashwagandha gummies every day?</summary><p>Yes. Clinical trials have demonstrated daily use for up to 12 weeks with no significant adverse effects. Some practitioners recommend cycling (2-3 months on, 2-4 weeks off) based on traditional Ayurvedic practice, though current evidence shows no tolerance development with continuous use. Long-term data beyond 12 months is limited.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Who should not take ashwagandha gummies?</summary><p>People with thyroid conditions (ashwagandha increases thyroid hormone production), autoimmune diseases, pregnant or breastfeeding women, anyone scheduled for surgery within 2 weeks, and people taking thyroid medication, immunosuppressants, sedatives, or blood sugar-lowering drugs without physician approval.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Are ashwagandha gummies as effective as capsules?</summary><p>At equivalent doses of the same extract, yes. A gummy with 300mg of KSM-66 delivers the same active compounds as a capsule with 300mg of KSM-66. The difference is practical: capsules can pack higher doses into a single unit, while gummies may require 2-3 per serving. Always compare milligrams of standardized extract, not marketing claims.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Does ashwagandha increase testosterone?</summary><p>Clinical evidence supports a modest testosterone increase in men — approximately 15% in an 8-week study of overweight men taking 600mg KSM-66 daily. The effect appears to work through cortisol reduction rather than direct hormonal stimulation. Ashwagandha does not raise testosterone above normal physiological ranges in healthy men.</p></details>
    </section>

